<br>
The problem is that fast damage should be a good enough mitagation of damage that a slower is not needed. A dead mob makes no more damage, however as good as our new damage potential is it doesn't drop these mobs fast enough to mitagate enough damage. I believe there should be a decrease in mob hps in much of PoP to the point where offensive power is as useable as defensive (slows). This would allow secondary healers to be more valuable, this would make high DPS characters more valuable, and would make average tanks more valuable (as they will only need to tank for so long per fight). The fights on regular xp mobs should be short enough where slow is only useful when you are LACKING the dps you should have. Slow is still valuable in a offensive poor group, and certainly still valuable in larger longer fights. <br>
<br>
The other alternative is for DPS dependant classes to get upgrades, however that would clearly have far reaching repurcussions in old zones, raids, pvp, etc. <br>
<br>
I see no problems with xp yardtrash having thier hps dropped (and perhaps a portion of their xp dropped as well), while leaving tougher mobs (with xp fully intact) for the groups who have it all in terms of offense and defense. This fixes grouping problems and allows for the occassional soloing. The only other change I can see that might need to be made is adding in a few more non snareable mobs so that all of the new lower hp mobs don't just become quadder fodder. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=heofmanyfals>HeOfManyFals</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 65<br> <font color=#333333>(2/3/03 5:39:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8676.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Doesn't work that way</span><hr size=1> The problem is, you are trying to examine a single kill.  Xping is made up of a constant stream of kills.<br>
<br>
DPS affects pull rate, it does not affect damage taken over a set period of time.<br>
<br>
Slow affects damage taken, it only indirectly affects kill rate.<br>
<br>
You can't really substitute one for the other.<br>
